description.plain:
Philadelphia-born Sabrina Annlynn Carpenter (born May 11, 1999) is an American singer-songwriter and actress. She made her debut as a child actress in Season 12, Episode 12 of Law & Order: Special Victims Unit. In 2013 and 2014, she lent her voice to Princess Vivian on Disney Junior’s Sofia The First.

In 2014, Carpenter landed her first major acting role as Maya Hart on Disney’s Girl Meets World, a spinoff of the hit sitcom Boy Meets World, in which she sang the theme song “Take On the World” with Rowan Blanchard. The same year, she released her first single, “Can’t Blame A Girl For Trying”, which received a Radio Disney Music Award.

In 2014, after signing with Hollywood Records, she released her debut EP, Can’t Blame a Girl for Trying. In 2015, she released her debut studio album, Eyes Wide Open. In 2016, lead single “On Purpose” preceded the release of her second studio album EVOLution, in which she experimented with a more mature pop sound and elements of dance and tropical house.

In 2018, the Philly pop star dropped her third album, Singular: Act I, followed by Act II a year later.

Carpenter’s fifth studio album, emails i can’t send, was released on July 2022, followed by singles from September 2021, “skinny dipping,” February 2022, “Fast Times,” and July 2022, “Vicious.” The fifth album track, “because i liked a boy,” also ended up being a single after the album’s release and was later certified gold.

In April 2024, Carpenter released the single “Espresso”, which quickly became her breakthrough hit, peaking at #3 on the Billboard Hot 100 and marking both her first top ten single and highest peak on the chart. This was followed by the announcement of her sixth studio album, Short n' Sweet, along with the release of the album’s second single “Please Please Please” in June, which went on to surpass “Espresso” and become her first #1 hit single on the Billboard Hot 100. Short n' Sweet was released on August 23, 2024, coinciding with the release of its third single “Taste”.

description.plain:
“Please Please Please” is the second single from Sabrina Carpenter’s sixth studio album, Short n' Sweet. The track captures a mix of affection, frustration, and concern. The lyrics explore the complexities of loving someone who might not always make the best decisions, and emphasize Carpenter’s desire to protect both her relationship and pride. It is rumored to be about her boyfriend, Barry Keoghan, who stars as Sabrina Carpenter’s love interest in the song’s music video.

The track was first teased on April 11, 2024, when a 4-second snippet was played in the police car at the end of the “Espresso” music video. Sabrina Carpenter posted the same snippet online on June 2, 2024, almost 2 months after it was initially heard. The following day, she teased the song’s announcement in the caption of the Short n' Sweet album announcement post:

i also have a surprise coming for you on thursday night so keep an eye out!!

As promised, on June 5, 2024, Sabrina Carpenter officially announced that “Please Please Please” would be the next single by posting the trailer for its music video.

songs.title: Bed Chem

description.plain:
Suited with the most sexually-provocative title, the sixth track from Sabrina Carpenter’s Short n' Sweet, “Bed Chem,” infers to Carpenter and her lover’s new-found chemistry, which is the longform of “chem.”

The track is speculated to be about Barry Keoghan of Saltburn fame; who wore a ‘white jacket’ when they first met at Givenchy’s fashion show for Paris Fashion Week in September last year.

The R&B-esque synths reminiscent of songs from the early 2000s were no coincidence, as, during an interview with Paper Magazine, Carpenter harkened her throwback sound from childhood tracks:

I love Christina Aguilera. [She] was one of my very first idols and icons. I was eleven years old and you couldn’t get her name out of my mouth. She’s very special to me. Those songs raised me.

songs.title: Taste

description.plain:
“Taste” is the first track off of Sabrina Carpenter’s sixth studio album, Short n’ Sweet. It was released as the highly anticipated third single from the album with a music video featuring female actress, Jenna Ortega on August 23rd, 2024, following smash hits “Espresso” & “Please Please Please”.

Disco-infused & irresistibly danceable, “Taste” serves as the album’s opener, layering risqué innuendos with revenge and betrayal, stating that even if he’s cheating, she’ll allow it as he’s always got the taste of her on his lips.

The music video, much like the track, cheekily references many dark satirical movies, such as Ginger Snaps, The Addams Family, & primarily Death Becomes Her, with Ortega playing Madeline, who’s played by Meryl Streep, & Carpenter playing Helen, who’s played by Goldie Hawn.

songs.title: Espresso

description.plain:
“Espresso” is the first single from Sabrina Carpenter’s sixth studio album, Short n' Sweet. In the song, Sabrina likens herself to the coffee as her partner can’t sleep when he’s with her. The funky pop single has Carpenter singing about how she can get a guy, and she is his dream came true. Carpenter references items and objects, like Mountain Dew, the Nintendo Switch console, and espresso coffee.

On April 4, 2024, Sabrina’s team teased that new music was “brewing”. Resulting on the single being officially announced four days later—beside a 7" vinyl and cassette—with a release date of April 11, 2024, alongside a radio-friendly clean version. Two days later, Carpenter performed the song live for the first time at Coachella.

On May 17, 2024, the Espresso EP was released containing six different versions of the song, including instrumental and acapella. This was followed by the “Espresso (Working Late Remix)” on May 31, 2024, by Mark Ronson.

The official music video was directed by Dave Meyers and its official lyric video was directed by Jes Sheldon.

“Espresso” reached #1 in the UK, Australia, and Ireland—Carpenter’s first number one in these countries—as well as peaking at #3 on the US Billboard Hot 100 and peaking at #2 on the US Billboard Mainstream Top 40 Hits in her home country; in addition to other charting success globally. On August 7, 2024, the single surpassed 1 billion streams on Spotify, Carpenter’s first song to achieve this.

description.plain:
Serving as an alleged response to Olivia Rodrigo’s wildly popular “drivers license,” “Skin” is a message to all the people that sent her hate for being with Joshua Bassett and also has lines that appear to be directly addressed at Rodrigo.

The song is Sabrina Carpenter’s first single release in 2021 and her first with her new record label Island Records. The song was a surprise release announced by Sabrina on her Twitter and Instagram on January 21, 2021.

songs.title: Good Graces

description.plain:
“Good Graces”, the third track on Short n' Sweet, is a confident and assertive song about setting boundaries in a relationship. The lyrics convey a message that while the singer can be sweet and loving, she won’t tolerate any disrespect or shady behavior (“You do somethin' sus, kiss my cute ass bye-bye”).

Carpenter warns her partner to stay in her “good graces” implying that if they don’t, she can quickly switch from love to indifference or even hatred.

Fittingly, this song plays right after “Please Please Please”, in which Carpenter is pleading with her partner to communicate and be honest with her. She is afraid of losing the person she loves and is desperately asking for reassurance that everything will be okay. It’s a song that captures the tension between love and fear.

In contrast to “Please Please Please”, this song emphasizes her strength and self-respect, making it clear that she won’t hesitate to move on if she’s not treated well.

songs.full_title: Slim Pickins by Sabrina Carpenter
songs.title: Slim Pickins

description.plain:
“Slim Pickins” delves into the process of trying to find the right guy—someone who’s attractive, kind, and smart, but not having a lot of luck in that endeavor. As she finds that it’s “slim pickings” (very few good things to choose from), she ponders the idea of ending up alone and decides to just settle for someone she doesn’t really love.

Carpenter first performed the track at the Grammy’s Museum on August 2, 2024. It was the only song to have been performed or directly teased prior to the album’s release.

songs.full_title: Busy Woman by Sabrina Carpenter
songs.title: Busy Woman

description.plain:
“Busy Woman” by Sabrina Carpenter was originally released on August 29th, 2024, as an exclusive bonus track on the digital re-issue of Short n’ Sweet, retitled Short n’ Sweet(er). Sabrina revealed that she wrote the song along side producer Jack Antonoff right after they wrapped up the album, meaning she couldn’t include it on the standard edition of the record, but decided to share it as an exclusive on the digital version. It was later included with the deluxe edition of the album, releasing digitally and physically on February 14, 2025.

In the song, Sabrina balances the mixed emotions of self-importance and desire in romantic relationships. Sabrina explains that because of her schedule as a pop-star she’s quite busy more often than not, but for the person she’s pursuing she’s willing to make a change in her everyday-life in order for them to be with her. Sabrina uses her signature humor infused sarcastic lines to confront the rejection she’s faced with from this person, warning them of the potential consequences if they reject her.

Sabrina heartbreakingly confesses that she knows her ex wasn’t the ‘sharpest tool’ in the metaphorical shed; and therefore knows that during their relationship together, there was nothing, in his eyes, deep about their love for each other; never talking about it as a result of the matter.

Meanwhile, during this withdrawal, the ex ends up seeing new girls, keeping Sabrina as a side piece for his own love life

songs.full_title: Don't Smile by Sabrina Carpenter
songs.title: Don’t Smile

description.plain:
“Don’t Smile”, the last track on Short n' Sweet, is about the aftermath of a breakup, where the singer expresses a mix of bitterness and longing.

The song takes the saying/quote “Don’t cry because it’s over, smile because it happened” and twists it; making it “Don’t smile because it happened, baby, cry because it’s over”.

The repeated phrase reflects Carpenter’s desire for her ex partner to feel sorrow and remorse rather than happiness about their past relationship. The lyrics reveal that she is hurt and struggling to move on, wishing that her ex would feel the same pain and regret that she does. She wants her ex to miss her and think about her when with someone new.

Interestingly, the first track on the album, “Taste”, is about the lingering presence and impact the singer has on her ex, even after they’ve moved on to someone new. The lyrics suggest that although the relationship is over, the ex still carries memories, habits, and even physical traces of the singer.

This makes for a cycle as Carpenter ends the album with wanting her ex partner to feel remorse and she starts the album with her ex feeling that remorse.

description.plain:
Sabrina Carpenter’s “Feather” is a disco-influenced pop song about cutting ties with a toxic relationship and feeling lighter as a result. In July 2023, the song was promoted as the lead single from the deluxe edition of Carpenter’s fifth studio album, emails i can’t send fwd:, as well as serving as the sixth overall single from the album.

During the tracking week ending December 16, 2023, the song debuted at #100 on the Billboard Hot 100 chart. During the tracking week ending April 27, 2024, the song reached a new peak of #21. The song marks Carpenter’s third appearance on the Hot 100, following “Skin” (#48) and “Nonsense” (#56).

songs.title: Thumbs

description.plain:
“Thumbs” was released on October 7, 2016 as a promotional single for Sabrina Carpenter’s sophomore album EVOLution, and was later released as an official single on January 3, 2017. It is the ninth song performed on Carpenter’s headline tour of the same name.

“Thumbs” is a song about not becoming someone who just goes along with everybody else and how everyone in the world is the same in some way.

This song is about how people go through the same routines every day without thinking. The main phrase of the chorus means that people may or may not see a problem in what is going on with what they or others are doing, but they do not do anything about it.  The saying “twiddle your thumbs” means “to do nothing for a period of time, usually while you are waiting for something to happen”.

Over a guitar-based instrumental, she plays on the nonsense concept and uses a humorous selection of terminology on the song’s pre-chorus and bridge.

Serving as the thirteenth track in the deluxe edition (2025) of Short n’ Sweet (2024), “15 Minutes” sees Sabrina intertwining the concept of time with playful sexual innuendos, and reflects on personal growth and how time shapes an individual. Through it, Sabrina contemplates her journey, and the moment she finds herself in, particularly in relation to her meteoric rise to fame.

The title “15 Minutes,” breaks the fourth wall by referencing the combined runtime of the deluxe tracks, which totals to around 15 minutes. It also might be a reference to the phrase “15 minutes of fame” and how Sabrina will do a lot with her “15 minutes” and then, when her time is up, she might “leak some pictures,” or “say something batshit crazy,” to get back into the spotlight and take advantage of the toxic “15 minutes of fame” mindset out of revenge.

songs.full_title: emails i can't send by Sabrina Carpenter
songs.title: emails i can’t send

description.plain:
On “emails i can’t send,” Carpenter shares her past from the perspective of a daughter who discovered that her father had an affair. The lyrics show the pain, disappointment, and lack of trust that came out of this situation over a melancholically beautiful and soft piano ballad.

Carpenter first teased the song on her Instagram and revealed that it would serve as the introductory track. Later, she had written about the inspiration behind the track for a Spotify Storyline:

the song that inspired the record. someone i looked up to let me down and it changed the way i love and receive love.

In a 2025 interview with Vogue, Carpenter was asked how her father handled the song:

Sure as hell did not play it for him in person. I sent it to my mother first. There were definitely feelings involved. But you birthed me, so you kind of have to deal with the repercussions.

songs.title: Why

description.plain:
“Why” is a single by Sabrina Carpenter, released on July 7th, 2017. The song is about her and a guy being completely opposite, but they’re made for each other.

She talked to Billboard about her first single and said

This song happened very quickly. We started with the first line of the song – ‘You like New York City in the daytime; I like New York City in the night time’ – and from there, the song kind of wrote itself. It’s basically [about] these differences that we all have, that keep us different from one another but at the same time glue us together. … I like to say it’s very conversational, which some of my other songs haven’t been before.

songs.title: A Nonsense Christmas

description.plain:
“A Nonsense Christmas” is Sabrina Carpenter’s holiday remix of her hit song “Nonsense” from her album emails i can’t send. She incorporates Christmas-themed wordplay and dirty jokes to give the song a holiday twist. The remix was originally released as a single on December 7th, 2022, and was later included on her Christmas EP fruitcake the following year.

A Netflix holiday special titled after the song, A Nonsense Christmas with Sabrina Carpenter, was released on December 6th, 2024, featuring live performances of the first four songs on the fruitcake EP along with other holiday standards.

songs.full_title: On Purpose by Sabrina Carpenter
songs.title: On Purpose

description.plain:
Written by Carpenter and Ido Zmishlany (who produced the track), this is the lead single from her sophomore album, EVOLution. Prior to its release, Carpenter teased the track on Instagram through a daily countdown.

“On Purpose” is an upbeat pop-dance song with elements of tropical house that celebrates a unexpected, budding relationship. The single marks a musical departure for Carpenter from the indie pop of Eyes Wide Open. It is the first song on the album track list, serving as an introduction to the theme of complicated relationships and maturity explored in EVOLution.

The music video, directed by James Miller, shows clips of Carpenter walking around London and Madrid.

description.plain:
“decode” is the thirteenth and final track on Sabrina Carpenter’s fifth album, emails i can’t send. The song touches on Carpenter’s inability to accept situations that are out her control. Being hard on herself and blaming herself for the entirety of the situation. This song is a reminder to herself to accept whatever happens in her life as it is. “You are past the point of asking questions and asking Whys and asking Hows. It just is what it is.” Carpenter says in an interview with Rolling Stone.

The track was first teased in a TikTok, posted on October 5, 2021.
